        <body>       

                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>New York 27<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Augt. &#39;86<lb/>
                144 E. 65<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> S. Morais<lb/>
                Phil<hi rend="sup">a</hi><lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir &#38; Colleague<lb/></p>
            <p>I have just read<lb/> your article in the Am&#58; Heb&#58; under the<lb/> caption of &#34;An Old Ritual.&#34;  It is both<lb/> interesting and suggestive.  In this connection<lb/> I wish to mention that I recently bought here<lb/> an old Sephardic P Book fr. &#91;Hebrew&#93; what I<lb/> have not been able to examine carefully; but I<lb/> notice a variation in the hymn &#91;Hebrew&#93; which has<lb/> two additional lines.  After &#91;Hebrew&#93; comes this&#58;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> after &#91;Hebrew&#93; comes&#58; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> In &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; instead of &#91;Hebrew&#93; as we use&#44; I find &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> In &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  In &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; a few verbal trans&#45;<lb/>&#61;positions.  In &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#58; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p> 
            <p>The Book is evidently of Amsterdam<lb/> imprint&#44; judging by the types &#38; general form&#44; tho<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the title page is missing.  On the blank leafes<sic></sic><lb/> I find the name of the owner viz&#58; &#34;Abm Cohen&#44;<lb/> Philadelphia Oct 14<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1785&#95;&#34; and also &#34;Lyon Moses<lb/> 1783.&#34; elsewhere.<lb/></p>
            <p>When I was in Venice some<lb/> 5 years ago&#44; I saw a Prayer Book in the<lb/> Portuguese Synagogue what had the body of<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; in two columns; one with our<lb/> usual form&#44; the other&#44; much different&#44; to<lb/> the extent indeed&#44; if my memory is correct&#44;<lb/> of the entire omission of reference to the &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/></p>
            <p>I believe you have touched<lb/> on a useful subject&#44; which I beg you will<lb/> pursue in future articles.  The good results<lb/> may be more far&#45;reaching than may be at<lb/> present perceptible.  I&#44; for one&#44; will be very glad<lb/> to read more from your pen on this topic&#44; &#38;<lb/> perhaps it may draw me other information.<lb/></p>
            <p>Let me thank you for your kind and<lb/> appreciated words of sympathy at the real&#91;&#63;&#93; loss<lb/> which has fallen on my wife and myself.  It<lb/> has been a great trial for both of us&#44; and the<lb/> wound still bleeds.  God help us&#33;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>With kind regards<lb/> yours truly<lb/> Henry S. Jacobs<lb/></p>
                
            <p>In another &#34;Portuguese&#34; PB&#44; I find various<lb/> Pizmonim for &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; before &#91;Hebrew&#93; before &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; before<lb/> taking out the &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#38;c; the &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#38; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> of the Ashkenazic ritual&#44; and the claling up of the<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; with the similar phrases used therein.  On &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> a great many added Pizmonim.  In Yigdal &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; and &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#38;c.  In &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#58; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            </body>
